<PageLayout title="About" description="About Shipwrite — a daily US market-impact publication covering stocks and real estate.">
	<h1>About Shipwrite</h1>
	<section>
		<p>
			Shipwrite is a daily market-impact publication focused on two lanes only: US stocks and US
			real estate. The goal is not to repost headlines, but to explain how the previous day's
			events flow through markets — the mechanism, the second-order effects, and what to watch next.
		</p>
		<p>
			Each edition begins with prior-day developments across policy, economics, diplomacy,
			regulation, and corporate news. From there, the research workflow expands into transmission
			chains and market consequences before publishing one stocks analysis and one real-estate analysis.
		</p>
	</section>
	<section>
		<h2>Editorial Team</h2>
		<p>
			Shipwrite content is produced by the <strong>Shipwrite Editorial Team</strong> — a group of
			market researchers and financial writers with backgrounds spanning equity analysis, fixed
			income, and US residential and commercial real estate. All published analyses draw on
			primary sources including government data releases, regulatory filings, institutional
			research, and reporting from established financial news organizations.
		</p>
		<p>
			Our editorial process follows a structured research-first workflow: source collection →
			evidence timeline construction → scenario analysis (base, upside, downside) → final review.
			Every factual claim is attributed to a named source. Uncertain or conflicting data is
			flagged explicitly rather than resolved arbitrarily.
		</p>
	</section>
	<section>
		<h2>Content focus</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>Stocks: sectors, policy transmission, earnings sensitivity, and market positioning</li>
			<li>Real Estate: mortgage rates, affordability, housing supply, refinancing waves, and regional spillovers</li>
			<li>Analysis first: facts, mechanism, uncertainty, and forward-looking indicators</li>
		</ul>
	</section>
	<section>
		<h2>Editorial standards</h2>
		<ul>
			<li>All analyses cite primary or institutional sources</li>
			<li>Conflicting institutional data is presented as-is, not resolved in favor of a single view</li>
			<li>Forward-looking statements are labeled as scenarios, not predictions</li>
			<li>No advertising content or sponsored analysis</li>
		</ul>
	</section>
	<section>
		<h2>Disclaimer</h2>
		<p>
			All content on Shipwrite is for informational purposes only and does not constitute
			investment, financial, real estate, or legal advice. Nothing published here is a
			recommendation to buy, sell, or hold any security or asset. Always consult a licensed
			financial advisor before making investment decisions. Past performance is not indicative
			of future results.
		</p>
	</section>
</PageLayout>
